trategy, you would:\n\n1. **Identify Keywords**:\n   - Use specific terms related to your topic (e.g., \"mycoplasma pneumoniae,\" \"pneumonia\").\n\n2. **Apply Boolean Logic**:\n   - Combine terms using AND, OR, and NOT to refine searches.\n\n3. **Use Database-Specific Filters**:\n   - Leverage database features for MEDLINE (e.g., language filters) or EMBASE (e.g., advanced search options).\n\n4. **Incorporate Sensitivity Strategies**:\n   - Use exclusionary terms to avoid irrelevant studies.\n   - Apply Dickersin 1994 strategy if needed.\n\n5. **Focus on Clinical Trials**:\n   - Include terms like \"randomized controlled trial\" or specific procedures (\"single blind procedure\").\n\n6. **Consult Additional Resources**:\n   - Check WHO ICTRP and ClinicalTrials.gov for specialized data.\n\n---\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nThis search strategy was designed to be comprehensive, targeting clinical studies involving mycoplasma pneumoniae and related conditions. By combining Boolean logic with specific keywords and sensitivity strategies, it aimed to retrieve high-quality, relevant literature while minimizing noise from non-published or irrelevant sources. To apply this approach in future work, focus on tailoring the keyword selection, adjusting Boolean combinations, and leveraging database-specific features for optimal results."}
